04204nam a22006375i 9780292793057DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212010txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927930577 a10.7560/7216852doi  a(DE-B1597)588107  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1219.56.C642bD684 2010eb 7aART0150502bisacsh04a972/.522221 aDouglas, Eduardo de J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn the Palace of Nezahualcoyotl :bPainting Manuscripts, Writing the Pre-Hispanic Past in Early Colonial Period Tetzcoco, Mexico /cEduardo de J. Douglas. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1 MIXED FORMS, MIXED MESSAGES: THE CODEX XOLOTL, THE QUINATZIN MAP, AND THE TLOHTZIN MAP -- t2 CEMANAHUACTLI IMACHIYO, “THE WORLD, ITS MODEL” -- t3 OUR KIN, OUR BLOOD -- t4 TELLING STORIES -- tCONCLUSION: IN THE PALACE OF NEZAHUALCOYOTL -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAround 1542, descendants of the Aztec rulers of Mexico created accounts of the pre-Hispanic history of the city of Tetzcoco, Mexico, one of the imperial capitals of the Aztec Empire. Painted in iconic script ("picture writing"), the Codex Xolotl, the Quinatzin Map, and the Tlohtzin Map appear to retain and emphasize both pre-Hispanic content and also pre-Hispanic form, despite being produced almost a generation after the Aztecs surrendered to Hernán Cortés in 1521. Yet, as this pioneering study makes plain, the reality is far more complex. Eduardo de J. Douglas offers a detailed critical analysis and historical contextualization of the manuscripts to argue that colonial economic, political, and social concerns affected both the content of the three Tetzcocan pictorial histories and their archaizing pictorial form. As documents composed by indigenous people to assert their standing as legitimate heirs of the Aztec rulers as well as loyal subjects of the Spanish Crown and good Catholics, the Tetzcocan manuscripts qualify as subtle yet shrewd negotiations between indigenous and Spanish systems of signification and between indigenous and Spanish concepts of real property and political rights. By reading the Tetzcocan manuscripts as calculated responses to the changes and challenges posed by Spanish colonization and Christian evangelization, Douglas's study significantly contributes to and expands upon the scholarship on central Mexican manuscript painting and recent critical investigations of art and political ideology in colonial Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAztec artzMexicozTexcoco de Mora. 0aAztecszMexicozTexcoco de MoraxHistoryvSources. 0aManuscripts, NahuatlzMexicozTexcoco de Mora. 0aPalaceszMexicozTexcoco de Mora. 7aART / History / Prehistoric & Primitive.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292793057423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292793057/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK